04523nam a22006015i 9780226263243DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20152015ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2015007717  a97802262632437 a10.7208/97802262632432doi  a(DE-B1597)550218  a(OCoLC)1050540963  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aLB1140.25.J3bH39 2015 4aLB1140 7aEDU0000002bisacsh04a372.2109522231 aHayashi, Akiko, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aTeaching Embodied :bCultural Practice in Japanese Preschools /cJoseph Tobin, Akiko Hayashi. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2015] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (224 p.) :b188 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- t1. Mimamoru (Teaching by Watching and Waiting -- t2. The Pedagogy of Feelings -- t3. The Pedagogy of Peripheral Participation -- t4. Learning Embodied Culture -- t5. Expertise -- t6. Early Childhood Education Policy as Cultural Practice -- t7. Reassembling the Cultural -- tAcknowledgments -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhen we look beyond lesson planning and curricula—those explicit facets that comprise so much of our discussion about education—we remember that teaching is an inherently social activity, shaped by a rich array of implicit habits, comportments, and ways of communicating. This is as true in the United States as it is in Japan, where Akiko Hayashi and Joseph Tobin have long studied early education from a cross-cultural perspective. Taking readers inside the classrooms of Japanese preschools, Teaching Embodied explores the everyday, implicit behaviors that form a crucially important—but grossly understudied—aspect of educational practice. Akiko Hayashi and Joseph Tobin embed themselves in the classrooms of three different teachers at three different schools to examine how teachers act, think, and talk. Drawing on extended interviews, their own real-time observations, and hours of video footage, they focus on how teachers embody their lessons: how they use their hands to gesture, comfort, or discipline; how they direct their posture, gaze, or physical location to indicate degrees of attention; and how they use the tone of their voice to communicate empathy, frustration, disapproval, or enthusiasm. Comparing teachers across schools and over time, they offer an illuminating analysis of the gestures that comprise a total body language, something that, while hardly ever explicitly discussed, the teachers all share to a remarkable degree. Showcasing the tremendous importance of—and dearth of attention to—this body language, they offer a powerful new inroad into educational study and practice, a deeper understanding of how teaching actually works, no matter what culture or country it is being practiced in.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aChild developmentzJapan. 0aEducation, PreschoolxPsychological aspects. 0aEducation, PreschoolzJapan. 0aEducational anthropology. 0aEducational psychologyzJapan. 0aPreschool teacherszJapan. 0aPreschool teachingzJapan. 0aTeachingxPsychological aspects. 7aEDUCATION / General.2bisacsh1 aTobin, Joseph, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311069043940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226263243423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226263243.jpg  a978-3-11-069043-9  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles